<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-dim-analysis-uncertainties-summary" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Summary</title>

  <p>
    Every chapter in this book has a summary section.
    This section is meant to be a concise summary of the main points covered in the chapter.
  </p>

  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          In science, quantities have dimensions, which are the physical nature of the quantity (e.g.
          length, time, mass, etc.), and units, which are the specific way we measure that quantity (e.g.
          meters, seconds, kilograms, etc.).
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The International System of Units (SI) is the most widely used system of units in the world.
          It consists of seven base units and seven associated defining constants, as delineated in <xref ref="tab-si-definitions"/>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Historically, the definitions of the base units were based on physical artifacts or specific physical phenomena.
          However, in 2019, the SI system was redefined to be based on fixed numerical values of fundamental physical constants, which provides a more stable and universal basis for the units.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Units composed of the base units are called derived units, and they can be expressed in terms of the base units.
          For example, the unit of force, the newton, is a derived unit that can be expressed as <m>\text{N} = \text{kg} \cdot \text{m} \cdot \text{s}^{-2}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Other systems of units, such as the CGS system, exist and are used in specific fields.
          Natural units, in which certain fundamental constants are set to 1, are used in theoretical physics to simplify equations and calculations.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          You can ascertain the relationship between different quantities by analyzing their dimensions.
          We explored how this applies to the period of a simple pendulum.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Every measurement comes with some degree of uncertainty, which represents the range of possible values that the true value of the quantity could take.
          An absolute uncertainty is a fixed amount of uncertainty, while a relative uncertainty is the ratio of the absolute uncertainty to the measured value.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Uncertainties propagate through calculations according to specific rules.
          If <m>L = x + y</m>, <m>A = xy</m>, <m>B = \frac{x}{y}</m>, and <m>C = x^n</m>, then the uncertainties propagate as follows:
          <md>
            <mrow>\Delta L \amp = \sqrt{(\Delta x)^2 + (\Delta y)^2} </mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{\Delta A}{A} \amp = \sqrt{\qty(\frac{\Delta x}{x})^2 + \qty(\frac{\Delta y}{y})^2} </mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{\Delta B}{B} \amp = \sqrt{\qty(\frac{\Delta x}{x})^2 + \qty(\frac{\Delta y}{y})^2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{\Delta C}{C} \amp = |n| \cdot \frac{\Delta x}{x}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Errors can be classified as random errors, which arise from unpredictable fluctuations in the measurement process, and systematic errors, which arise from consistent biases in the measurement process.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Random errors can be reduced by taking multiple measurements and averaging them.
          The mean has a uncertainty given by the standard error
          <me>
            \Delta \bar{x} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{N}}
          </me>,
          where <m>\sigma</m> is the standard deviation of the measurements and <m>N</m> is the number of measurements.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Data can be visualized on a graph, and the uncertainty can be represented as error bars on the graph.
          A line of best fit can be drawn through the data points to represent the relationship between the variables.
          The <m>R^2</m> value of the line of best fit indicates how well the line fits the data, with a value of 1 indicating a perfect fit and a value of 0 indicating no correlation.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Relationships can be linearized to make it easier to analyze the data and determine the relationship between the variables.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Fermi problems are estimation problems that involve making educated guesses about quantities that are difficult to measure directly.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>
